solutions.content:
Hi, this is a combination of counting occurrences of characters, and not allowing certain characters to appear after others. For example, it is simple to deduce that "b" can never appear after another "b", and "c" can never appear after an "a". 

So we scan first to check for wrong occurrences, and then we scan again to count the occurrences of each character. In the second loop, we are careful not to have more "b's" than "a's" or more "c's" than "b's". 

````
class Solution {
    public boolean isValid(String S) {
        int[] abc = new int[3];
        if(S.length() < 3) return false;
        char f = S.charAt(0);
        for(int i = 1; i < S.length(); i++){
            if(f == 'a'){
                if(S.charAt(i) == 'c') return false;
            }
            else if(f == 'b'){
                if(S.charAt(i) == 'b') return false;
            }
            f = S.charAt(i);
        }
        for(int i = 0; i < S.length(); i++){
            char c = S.charAt(i);
            if(c == 'a'){
                abc[0]++;
            }
            if(c == 'b'){
                if(abc[1] >= abc[0]) return false;
                abc[1]++;
            }
            if(c == 'c'){
                if(abc[2] >= abc[1]) return false;
                abc[2]++;
            }
        }

        return abc[0] == abc[1] && abc[1] == abc[2];
    }
}
````

