**Solution1: two-index**

Have two pointers (idx1 and idx2) pointing at the beginning of the 1st half and 2nd half of the input array respectively, then fill in the result array by moving idx1 and idx2 rightward alternatly. 

Time complexity and space complexity are both O(n).

```
public class Solution {
    public int[] Shuffle(int[] nums, int n) {

        if(nums == null || nums.Length == 0)
            return nums;

        int[] res = new int[2 * n];
        int idx1 = 0, idx2 = n;

        for(int i = 0; i < 2 * n; i++)
        {
            if(i % 2 == 0)
                res[i] = nums[idx1++];
            else
                res[i] = nums[idx2++];
        }

        return res;
    }
}
```


