You could do it with an in-place sort, based on the original indexes. JavaScript doesn't have the index or actually sort in-place, but here is a working solution that demonstrates the idea:

```javascript
return nums
    .map((val, index) => new Object({ val, index }))
    .sort((first, second) => {
        if (first.index >= n) {
            if (second.index >= n) return first.index - second.index;
            else return (first.index - n) - second.index;
        } else {
            if (second.index >= n) return first.index - (second.index - n);
            else return first.index - second.index;
        }
    })
    .map(elem => elem.val);
```

